WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
6 new English from BBCLearningEnglish.com.

2
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello and welcome to 6 minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

3
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
I'm Georgie.

4
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I'm Neil.

5
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Georgie, today we're talking about cooking oils and which products are best for our health.

6
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:21.000
What do you use to cook with?

7
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Olive oil butter, maybe avocado oil.

8
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:31.000
When I want my food to be rich and creamy, I use butter but usually for everyday meals.

9
00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:33.000
I just use olive oil. What about you?

10
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Yes, it varies.

11
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.000
But I guess for East Asian food I might sometimes use sesame oil.

12
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Now, there are so many different oils we can use for our food and some of them are very expensive and claim to have big health benefits.

13
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Today we'll be finding out whether these products are worth the money and can really help us eat more healthily.

14
00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Yes, and don't forget to go to our website for a transcript of this program to read along and a worksheet to test what you've learnt.

15
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Visit BBCLearningEnglish.com.

16
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
OK, Georgie, let's start with a question.

17
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
In the UK, a popular oil to cook with is olive oil.

18
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.000
But which country produces the most olive oil?

19
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Is it a Italy, B, Greece or C Spain?

20
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Ooh, that's difficult. I know that Spain produces a lot but I think I'm going to go with Italy.

21
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.000
OK, well we'll find out if that's the right answer at the end of the program.

22
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Now, lots of us are careful about the amount of fat we eat.

23
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:43.000
We might avoid fast food and treats like chocolate or cake, but lots of the fat we eat comes from the oils we cook with.

24
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:48.000
Yes, and some expensive oils claim to contain other vitamins that are good for us.

25
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
But are these claims true? It can be confusing.

26
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Presenter of BBC Radio 4 programme Sliced Bread, Greg Furt, has lots of emails about the problem.

27
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:03.000
I tell you what, Sarah, we have had an absolute what-load of emails sent to sliced.bread at BBC.com.

28
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:05.000
OK, asking about cooking oils.

29
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:14.000
Ah, listen to Alistair in Midlothian wrote that for years, we were told to cook with polyunsaturated oils like sunflower oil.

30
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.000
But now all the YouTube Doctor experts are telling us sea doils are harmful.

31
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:24.000
They advocate consuming extra virgin olive oil, but as I understand it, that's not suitable for frying a fish.

32
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Also, I hear that over a certain temperature olive oil turns harmful.

33
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
What the heck do I use for frying and roasting?

34
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Greg says that he's received a walk-load of emails.

35
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.000
A load of something is a lot of something.

36
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
You'll also commonly hear the expression shared load or truck load.

37
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
These are used to emphasise how much of something there is.

38
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:54.000
Yes, and Greg uses walk-load as a fun expression because he's talking about cooking oils and a walk is a kind of pan.

39
00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:04.000
Greg reads one of the emails from a confused listener, Alistair, who says that he's watched YouTube videos that argue that oils like sunflower oil are bad for you.

40
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
These videos advocate using extra virgin olive oil.

41
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
If you advocate something, you encourage people to use it.

42
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:18.000
But Alistair has also heard bad things about olive oil and that you can't use it at high temperatures.

43
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.000
He asks, what the heck can he use for roasting and frying?

44
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
What the heck is an informal phrase we can use to express frustration or surprise?

45
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.000
It does seem like there's a lot of advice about cooking oils and that not everyone agrees.

46
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:38.000
Yes, and some of the advice is to use very expensive options such as coconut oil and avocado oil.

47
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
People who advocate using these oils say they are wonder products.

48
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
A wonder product is an item, usually a food or medicine that is very effective or beneficial for people.

49
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:53.000
But not everyone is convinced that expensive cooking oils are worth the money.

50
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Neta Faruhi is professor of population health and nutrition at the University of Cambridge.

51
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:07.000
And she talked to BBC Radio for's sliced bread host Greg Foot about expensive cooking oils like avocado oil.

52
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
What do you think, Neta, what might justify the price tag?

53
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Certainly avocado oil is good for all the reasons mentioned, but is it worth justifying the cost?

54
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:27.000
If you're a particular connoisseur of the tasted brings and you prefer it and you have the money, then knock yourself out.

55
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:34.000
But there's lots of myths around these super foods and wonder oils and wonder this and that.

56
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:38.000
And it's just all I'm afraid hogwash.

57
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Neta says that avocado oil does have some health benefits, but she's not sure they are worth the cost of a bottle.

58
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:50.000
She says if you like the taste and are happy to spend the money then knock yourself out.

59
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:53.000
The expression knock yourself out means go ahead.

60
00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:00.000
But Neta is also concerned about all the health claims about expensive wonder products like avocado oil.

61
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:07.000
She says that many claims are hogwash. They are nonsense and products are not worth spending money on.

62
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Maybe I'll stick to my olive oil then and that reminds me of your question Neil.

63
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Yes, I asked you which country produces the most olive oil?

64
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
And I said Italy.

65
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
And I'm afraid you are wrong.

66
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
It is in fact Spain.

67
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:31.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this program starting with a load of something, which means a lot of something.

68
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
We also commonly hear shed load and truck load.

69
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:39.000
You advocate something, you encourage people to use it or do it.

70
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.000
The expression what the heck is used to express frustration or surprise.

71
00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:48.000
A wonder product is something that people think is very effective or beneficial.

72
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:51.000
The expression knock yourself out means go ahead.

73
00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:56.000
And if something is described as hogwash, it's nonsense or not true.

74
00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Once again, our six minutes are up.

75
00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:03.000
Try the free interactive quiz on our website to test the vocabulary you've learned.

76
00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
www.bbclanninginglish.com.

77
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Goodbye for now.

78
00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Goodbye.
